  "summary": "On an underground metro platform, a man loses his balance and falls toward an approaching train. Despite an intense fear of death, Sylas Hammel decides to sacrifice himself to save the man. Hammel uses his remaining strength to pull the man back onto the platform, but in doing so, he falls onto the tracks himself. As he dies, Hammel experiences a sense of freedom and hears the sound of Pan's flute and the flapping of wings.\n\nThe narrative shifts to France, where Lor Dobler, a thirty-two-year-old engineer, crosses the Seine River to visit an apartment in the Caudinet. He is greeted by Elise, an elderly and devout Catholic woman. Elise expresses her disapproval of the séances conducted by her mistress, Mademoiselle Simonne, claiming the practice is a deal with the devil that has left the lady pale, weak, and prone to headaches.\n\nDobler attempts to soothe Elise, explaining that the séances will cease once he marries Simonne. He defends Simonne’s character, asserting that she is an honest person and the best medium in France rather than a con artist. Elise remains fearful, suggesting that mediumship goes against nature and that the souls being contacted might not want to let Simonne go. The tension is interrupted by the arrival of Simonne, a tall, elegant, blonde woman. Dobler greets her affectionately but notes her extreme paleness and questions her health.",
